pr_body:
Closes #1903

This PR adds the feature to **export MIT App Inventor 2 projects as Android App Bundles (.aab)**, to be distributed through Google Play Store. This is part of my Google Summer of Code 2020 project proposal.

Changes in this pull can be seen live at [aab.appinventor.barreiro.xyz](https://aab.appinventor.barreiro.xyz).
Some useful docs can be found in [this folder](https://drive.google.com/drive/folders/1272Jn5iQ4T9rfmktMD8O5MDoc0gGnJEV?usp=sharing).

_Maybe this should be merged with "Squash & Merge" to just make a single commit with the feature._
pr_labels: [{'name': 'pull request: needs reply to review'}, {'name': 'feature request'}, {'name': 'affects: master'}]

pr_body:
> ⚠️ This branch actually takes as base the one with the AAB changes ([barreeeiroo:gsoc](https://github.com/barreeeiroo/appinventor-sources/tree/gsoc)). So, it is required to merge #2237 before this one, and after doing so it will be rebased onto the new master branch.
> As it takes the AAB branch as base, if you wish to view the changes in the "Files changed" tab, you will have to scroll down to the `appinventor/buildserver/src/com/google/appinventor/buildserver/BuildType.java` file. All changes from this file (included) to the bottom, are related with the refactor.

This is the work done as part of the extension to my Google Summer of Code project. After finishing implementing Android App Bundles, I then proceeded with a refactor to the famous `Compiler.java` file, with nearly 3,000 lines of code.
The idea behind this change is split each "task" into its own file, modularizing the current compiler so tasks can be re-used with different build outputs (thinking about iOS version). It also improves maintainability, as it is easier to debug a file with 200 lines of code rather than multiple methods in a single class.

Basically, the `Compiler` file disappears, and `ProjectBuilder` changes a bit to create two new objects: `ExecutorContext` and `Executor`. In `ExecutorContext` it is needed to specify the build props (the legacy constructor parameters that were being sent to `Compiler`), and then `Executor` specifies the context and the build type. Then, `Executor` can receive as many `Task` instances as they want, allowing to use the same tasks in different build types.
_I am still writing documentation and adding some more comments to the new files. This is just a very small summary of the implementation._

- [x] Fix code styling issues
- [ ] Add flag to disable color output
- [x] Finish documentation (create README.md in buildserver/)
- [x] Improve extensions unzipping (duplicated code in GenerateClasses and RunMultidex)
